    "date": "2018-01-24",
    "comment": "Rationale: Experiments in primary hippocampal cultures show that immunolabeling of endogenous Prr7 is enhanced in the nucleus after glutamate treatment while its synaptic localization is decreased. FRAP experiments confirmed the redistribution of the protein to the nucleus after glutamate application by using overexpression of Prr7-GFP. Use of photoconvertible Prr7-mEos3 further confirmed this.. Experimental description: Experiments were performed in rat primary hippocampal cultures.\n\n\"Antibodies used were as follows: PRR7 (1:2,000, Rb polyclonal; for imaging) a gift from Yoshinori Fujiyoshi (Nagoya University) and PRR7 (1:1,000, mouse monoclonal; Thermo Scientific) both were previously described (Murata et al, 2005; Hrdinka et al, 2011)\".\nFrom Hrdinka et al., 2011: \"Hybridomas producing monoclonal antibodies (mAbs, TRAP-3/01-13) to human PRR7 were prepared by standard hybridoma techniques using mice immunized with the recombinant protein corresponding to aa 147-274.\"\n\n\"Plasmids encoding human PRR7, PRR7-GFP, and PRR7(1-44)-GFP were generated previously (Hrdinka et al, 2011).\"",
